article.headline: McCarville leads Gophers' balanced attack
article.linkText: Minnesota's opening 24-4 run helps dust Northwestern
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota fans have been worrying about
Lindsay Whalen's injury for the past ten days, but the Gophers'
solid play on Sunday could help to ease their minds.

Playing at home for the first time in two weeks, the No. 11
Gophers raced out to a 24-4 lead and defeated Northwestern 73-46 as
13,222 fans welcomed home the Whalen-less Gophers.

Minnesota (20-5, 9-5 Big Ten) lost Whalen -- an all-America
candidate averaging 20.7 points per game -- to a broken hand on Feb.
12 in a loss at Ohio State. They split games at Illinois and Iowa
before coming back to their raucous fans at Williams Arena.

"It was a great atmosphere to play in," Northwestern coach
June Olkowski said. "If you were trying to keep Lindsay Whalen's
injury a secret, everybody we ran into from the airport to
restaurants to the hotel told us about it. I think it's a tribute
to Lindsay, to (Minnesota coach Pam Borton) and the administration
here, and it shows what they've done for women's college basketball
in this state."

Whalen will miss the remainder of the regular season but could
return in time for the NCAA tournament in late March.

Minnesota used a balanced attack with four players in double
figures to reach 20 victories for the third straight season. Janel
McCarville scored 20 points on 9-of-11 shooting, while Shannon
Schonrock hit four 3-pointers en route to 18 points.

"I think people are still learning their new roles," Borton
said. "I was telling my staff the other day, it feels like it's
November right now. We knew we'd have to replace Lindsay next
November but we'd have six months to prepare. Instead, we had two
days to prepare for our first game without her."

Schonrock, a sophomore point guard, will carry more of the
offensive load. She made 6 of 14 shots from the field Sunday,
including four 3-pointers.

"I know there's going to be more on me now, with Lindsay out of
the lineup," Schonrock said.

Freshman Kelly Roysland replaced Whalen in the starting lineup
and scored 11 points while dishing out five assists, and Shannon
Bolden added 10 points and seven assists for Minnesota.

Roysland opened the game with a 3-pointer from the corner and
surged to a 9-2 lead on a dish from Roysland to McCarville down
low. Minnesota took control for good with a 15-0 run that included
consecutive 3-pointers by Schonrock, Roysland and Bolden for a 24-4
lead.

"In the first half, we came out strong and really took it at
them," said McCarville, who had a game-high nine rebounds. "From
that point on, we put them back on their heels."

Alex Mueller was 4-of-6 from 3-point range and had 16 points for
Northwestern (8-18, 1-14), which opened the second half with a 10-0
run to slice into Minnesota's 45-21 halftime edge. Mueller hit a
3-pointer from the corner to cut Minnesota's lead to 49-36 with 15
minutes to play, but the Wildcats never got closer.

Olkowski said the Gophers don't necessarily need Whalen to make
some noise in the postseason.

"I think teams not in the Big Ten may overlook Minnesota
because Lindsay's not ready to play," Olkowski said. "But I think
McCarville and Schonrock will have something to say about it."
